        Listing Your Brisbane Home for Sale in December: Is It Worth It?
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        December is not the property dead zone most sellers assume. Here is an honest look at what actually happens to Brisbane's inner-east market over Christmas and New Year, and how to make the timing work for you.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most sellers assume December is a bad time to list. The holidays are approaching, families are distracted, and the conventional wisdom is that you should wait for the new year or hold until the spring selling season. That thinking is understandable, but it is not always accurate, and for some properties in Brisbane's inner east it is actively wrong. December can be a very good time to sell, with the important caveat that you need to understand precisely what kind of buyer activity to expect and how to structure your campaign accordingly.</p>

      <p>The first thing to understand is that Brisbane's summer is not comparable to a northern hemisphere winter slowdown. School holidays do reduce the frequency of open homes and there is genuine buyer distraction in the lead-up to Christmas, but the pool of qualified buyers watching the market does not disappear. Many of those buyers have been active since September and are frustrated at missing out during a busy spring. By December, some of them are highly motivated, have done their research, and are ready to act before year end.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The case for listing in December</h2>
      <p>The single strongest argument for a December campaign is reduced competition. The sellers who listen to conventional advice pull back from the market in November and December, which means the stock of available listings thins considerably. If your property is well-presented and competitively priced, you will face fewer comparable listings competing for the same buyers. In a market where buyers have limited choice, you are negotiating from a position of advantage rather than competing in a crowded field.</p>

      <p>A second factor is buyer quality. The buyers attending open homes in the first two weeks of December are typically not casual browsers. People who are actively viewing property in early December generally have a genuine motivation to purchase. They may need to settle before the financial year, have finance pre-approved and a deadline attached, or have sold their own property and be under pressure to buy. Tyre-kickers tend to stay home in December. The buyer pool is smaller, but the intent level is higher.</p>

      <p>For certain property types, summer is also actively beneficial. A home with a pool, good cross-ventilation, outdoor entertaining space, or a north-facing living area that captures breezes will present at its best in December and January. Brisbane buyers understand outdoor living, and a property that demonstrates that lifestyle clearly in summer photography will convert interest to inspections more readily than it might in a grey August.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The real risks of December and January</h2>
      <p>The main risk is timing the launch wrong. A campaign that starts too late in December, say after the second week, can run into a genuine quiet period that is difficult to recover from. Listings that go live on December 20 or later are unlikely to attract meaningful buyer attention until mid-January, and by that point the campaign has been live for three to four weeks without momentum. Buyers and their agents know when a property has been sitting, and a stale listing that re-emerges in late January carries a stigma that is hard to shift.</p>

      <p>There is also the vendor lifestyle consideration. Running a sale campaign in December means keeping the property presentable through the Christmas period, accommodating inspections during what is often a busy family time, and maintaining focus on negotiations when your attention may naturally be elsewhere. For some sellers, this is a genuine constraint. For others, particularly those who are already organised and motivated, it is manageable.</p>

      <p>January itself is typically the quietest month. The first two weeks of January see very low buyer activity as most of the market is still on holiday. Activity picks up noticeably from the third week of January and tends to be strong through February and March, as buyers who have been waiting through the holiday period come back energised and competitive. If your property is not under contract by late December, it is often worth discussing with your agent whether to pause the listing and relaunch in late January with refreshed photography and a renewed push.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Whether to withdraw or pause a listing</h2>
      <p>Withdrawing or pausing a listing is a legitimate tactic, but it needs to be done intentionally rather than as a reaction to a slow campaign. If your property goes live in early December and attracts strong interest but no acceptable offers by the third week, it is worth having a direct conversation with your agent about whether to pause over Christmas and relaunch in the last week of January. The key risk with pausing is that the days on market clock continues, and when you relaunch, buyers can see how long the property has been available. If you are going to pause, refresh the campaign properly when you come back, updating the copy, photography if possible, and the price guidance if that is warranted by the feedback you received in round one.</p>

      <p>Withdrawing entirely and relisting as a new listing is a more significant reset, but it does restart the days on market counter. It is generally only worth doing if the property has been significantly overpriced, the presentation has been reworked, or there is a substantive change that justifies presenting it as a new campaign. Relisting the same property at the same price with the same photos but a new listing date rarely fools buyers who are watching the market closely.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Practical timeline for a December launch</h2>
      <p>If you are considering selling in December, the timing of your launch matters more than in other months. A campaign that goes live between December 1 and December 12 gives you a genuine two-week window of active buyer engagement before Christmas. That is enough time to hold two or three open homes, generate offers, and potentially exchange contracts before year end. Settlement can then occur in late January or early February, which suits many buyers as well.</p>

      <p>A campaign launching after December 15 is unlikely to produce a result before Christmas. If your property is not going to be ready until then, it is often worth waiting until the last week of January and launching with full preparation rather than rushing into a thin market. The two weeks you save by listing in mid-December rarely justify the risk of the campaign losing momentum.</p>

      <p>If you are weighing a December launch against waiting for spring 2027, consider what waiting actually costs. Seven months of holding costs, additional maintenance, and the opportunity cost of not proceeding with whatever comes next add up. For most vendors who are ready to sell and whose property is well-prepared, a careful December campaign with a competent agent is a stronger option than an indefinite wait.</p>

